00:01:29.315 --> 00:01:32.615
First up is malware or malicious software.

00:01:33.005 --> 00:01:36.875
It's designed to cause damage
or just be plain irritating.

00:01:37.295 --> 00:01:38.914
We have different types here.

00:01:39.304 --> 00:01:41.645
Viruses are like clingy relatives.

00:01:41.855 --> 00:01:46.295
They attach themselves to legitimate
software and need a host to spread.

00:01:46.775 --> 00:01:48.664
Worms are more independent.

00:01:48.875 --> 00:01:53.104
They are self-replicating and spread
across networks all by themselves.

00:01:53.405 --> 00:01:54.310
No host needed.

00:01:55.150 --> 00:01:57.940
Trojan horses are the masters of disguise.

00:01:58.300 --> 00:02:02.290
They look like useful software,
but they hide malicious code.

00:02:02.710 --> 00:02:05.590
They trick you, but they
don't self-replicate.

00:02:06.190 --> 00:02:08.590
Ransomware is the digital kidnapper.

00:02:08.830 --> 00:02:11.770
It encrypts your files
and demands A ransom.

00:02:12.190 --> 00:02:14.350
Spyware is the neighborhood gossip.

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:17.830
It secretly watches and
collects your information.

00:02:18.430 --> 00:02:23.080
Adware is that annoying salesman
who just keeps showing unwanted ads.

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:27.220
And key loggers are the worst
kind of spies, recording

00:02:27.279 --> 00:02:29.200
every single thing you type.

00:02:29.619 --> 00:02:34.420
Next is phishing, a social engineering
trick where attackers pretend to

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:39.130
be someone trustworthy, like your
organization, to fool you into giving

00:02:39.130 --> 00:02:41.469
up sensitive info like passwords.

00:02:41.619 --> 00:02:43.029
Usually through email.

00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:45.010
Then we have spoofing.

00:02:45.310 --> 00:02:49.750
This is the art of disguise, faking
communication from a known source.

00:02:50.070 --> 00:02:53.490
It can be email spoofing,
IP spoofing, you name it.

00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:56.700
It's often the tool used
in a phishing attack.

00:02:57.150 --> 00:03:03.900
Imagine a DOS or DDOS attack as creating
a massive traffic jam to make a website

00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:06.720
on network unavailable to its real users.

00:03:07.090 --> 00:03:12.310
And finally, unauthorized access is
simply breaking and entering into a system

00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:18.040
without permission, often because of weak
passwords or trickery security measures.

00:03:18.370 --> 00:03:22.120
So how do we fight back
with a good firewall?

00:03:22.425 --> 00:03:27.375
It's the security guard for your network
monitoring all incoming and outgoing

00:03:27.375 --> 00:03:30.045
traffic and blocking anything suspicious.

00:03:30.525 --> 00:03:32.715
We also have antivirus software.

00:03:32.865 --> 00:03:36.855
The police force that detects,
prevents and removes malware.

00:03:37.390 --> 00:03:40.810
Encryption is like writing
your data in a secret code.

00:03:41.230 --> 00:03:46.060
There's symmetric encryption, which
uses one secret key for both locking

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:52.240
and unlocking and asymmetric encryption,
which uses a pair of keys, a public key to

00:03:52.240 --> 00:03:54.670
lock it, and a private key to unlock it.

00:03:55.055 --> 00:03:57.275
Of course you need strong passwords.

00:03:57.454 --> 00:03:59.585
